<TEXT>
the foreign ministry sent a formal 
protest to the united nations on friday alleging us violations of 
panamas sovereignty during a firefight involving us marines this 
week 
the protest said us troops closed a panamanian highway just 
outside the capital for three hours tuesday night after fighting 
broke out between soldiers of the united states and an unknown 
group 
at a news conference called by the us military marine 1st 
sgt alexander j nevglovski sr said friday that his company 
became engaged in a gunfight tuesday night at a fuel depot with 
uniformed men who were using us as training aids 
they were highly professional nevglovski who has served 
for 24 years in the marine corps told the news conference at the 
us southern commands headquarters they were good they were 
trying to provoke us 
nevglovski of camp lejeune nc said the intruders wore black 
uniforms and carried sophisticated night vision equipment but 
declined to speculate on whether they were members of the 
panamanian defense forces 
in the protest sent to un secretarygeneral javier perez de 
cuellar foreign minister jorge abadia called the highway closing a 
flagrant violation of panamas sovereignty by us troops 
according to earlier reports the highway was closed after about 
100 marines exchanged fire with what they described as 40 to 50 
uniformed intruders at the fuel dump near howard air force base a 
few miles west of panama city 
the us southern command said it consulted with the defense 
forces before closing the highway for security reasons 
col ron sconyers the southern commands chief spokesman said 
nevglovski was presented at the news conference friday to answer 
reporters questions because of skeptical reports in the united 
states and ridicule in the panamanian press which is largely 
controlled by the government 
nevglovski told of two separate firefights tuesday night and 
said that during one eight marines and a sailor were surrounded by 
a group of intruders about half a mile from the sergeants position 
no casualties were reported tuesday but a us marine was shot 
and fatally wounded by fellow marines in an incident monday 
nevglovski said the fatal shooting occurred as the marines tried to 
encircle eight intruders wearing black uniforms and moving in 
military fashion 
the defense forces are commanded by gen manuel antonio noriega 
who is under federal indictment in the united states on drug 
trafficking charges the united states has imposed economic 
sanctions against panama in an effort to force noriega who 
dominates the civilian government to resign 
sconyers said a full investigation into the actions monday and 
tuesday was under way 
the united states maintains about 10000 military personnel in 
panama as a permanent force to defend the panama canal about 1300 
additional us soldiers and marines were sent to panama last week 
to increase security 
the panamanian government has described the us marines as 
inexperienced troops who were shooting at swaying palm trees 
nevglovskis account of tuesdays incidents left unanswered the 
questions of who were the intruders and why in more than two hours 
of sporadic gunfire were there apparently no injuries on either 
side 
he was asked to assess the intruders motives and the sergeant 
replied 
they were basically using us as training aides to see how 
they can get around and how they cant get around to see how they 
can get detected and how they cant get detected 
nevglovski raised a new question when he said marines did not 
chase the intruders into the surrounding jungle because a month or 
so earlier two air force mps chased an intruder into the jungle 
and one was hacked to death with a machete and the other was cut up 
pretty bad 
no such incident had been announced and after the news 
conference military spokesmen said nevglovski had repeated a rumor 
that had no basis in fact 
and while nevglovski said he had a group of about 42 intruders 
almost constantly in view with a nightvision device i didnt 
see a weapon on them i cant say why we could see them clearly 
he said of the shooting we received the first three rounds 
and our return fire lasted about 15 minutes what i could 
identify was three or four muzzle flashes coming from a certain 
area 
at that time i immediately went to my machine gunner and 
tapped him on the shoulder and told him to return fire 
nevglovski said he returned fire approximately 10 or 15 rounds 
and i tapped him again and told him to cease fire 
nevglovski said another marine opened fire at the same time with 
a second machine gun but none of the marines used their weapons 
or pistols because the word hadnt been given to open fire 
nevglovski said that while he and about 90 other marines were 
engaged with more than 40 intruders another group of nine american 
servicemen were surrounded by about 10 other intruders on a 
hill half a mile away 
the two groups were in radio contact nevglovski said and at 
least three 80mm mortar rounds were fired at the intruders 
positions 
</TEXT>
