<TEXT>
jai alai players went on strike in 
connecticut rhode island and florida on thursday to protest what 
they say are unfair working conditions and harassment since 
organizing a union earlier this year 
richard aries a lawyer for the 500member international jai 
alai players association said the strike affected frontons in 
bridgeport hartford and newport ri and many of the 10 frontons 
in florida 
frontons are buildings that house courts where the handballlike 
game is played before spectators who bet on the matches 
people who answered the telephones in hartford and bridgeport 
said the frontons werent open because players werent working 
there was no answer at the rhode island facility 
in florida two frontons in melbourne and west palm beach 
canceled performances thursday frontons in miami and quincy fla 
remained open using nonstriking and substitute players 
officials at all frontons in florida except ocala and fort 
pierce said they expected to be open friday the others are in 
tampa fla and daytona beach fla 
aaron carbone a spokesman for the hartford fronton said 
management signed about six players thursday night and expected to 
have between 15 and 20 players ready for fridays program 
there are about 550 jai alai players in the three states aries 
said he said about 90 percent of them have joined the association 
aries said that members of the association have been forbidden 
from wearing the unions insignia and that at least five players 
have been told their contracts will be terminated 
the players were unable to tolerate the continuing harassment 
and intimidation that has followed their organizing into an 
association aries said they had put up with a lot during the 
course of their regular employment with contracts that allowed 
fronton owners to dominate them 
the national labor relations board has conducted hearings in 
hartford boston and miami on the associations request that 
federal officials oversee union authorization votes at the 14 
frontons in the united states 
aries said there have been no decisions from the hartford and 
boston nlrb offices and the hearings are continuing in miami 
</TEXT>
