<TEXT>
senate passage of a 11 trillion fiscal 1989 
budget sets up a battle with the house over domestic spending and 
how far congress can stray from its deficitreduction pact with 
president reagan 
this years budget debate is framed by the bipartisan agreement 
with the president which sets out limits for taxes and major 
spending categories 
both the house and senate have now passed budgets obeying the 
pacts spending caps of 294 billion for the military and 161 
billion in foreign aid and neither chamber included tax increases 
beyond the 14 billion enacted last december 
so when the two sides begin meeting next week to resolve their 
differences the focus will be on domestic programs 
the senate plan approved thursday by a 6926 vote is similar 
to the house plan in supporting large increases in spending on aids 
research education and aviation safety both also reject reagans 
request to terminate several domestic programs 
but the senate plan is closer to the presidents in several 
areas it contains sharp increases for the space program and 
science the house last month opted for more modest boosts in those 
areas in order to better protect mass transit housing and 
development programs 
both plans fudge the numbers in order to claim they stay within 
the domestic spending limits but they do it in different ways 
the house voted to use what senate budget committee chairman 
lawton chiles dfla called creative accounting simply 
declaring that some expenses were not covered by the agreement 
the senate eager to make room for a new 26 billion antidrug 
program but unwilling to make cuts elsewhere in the budget at the 
last minute set up a special fund declaring the money wouldnt be 
tapped unless a dire emergency were declared the budget simply 
doesnt count that spending yet 
still budget leaders from the two chambers said they hoped to 
reach agreement quickly 
there are obvious differences house budget committee 
chairman william h gray iii dpa said in a written statement 
with good will i am sure these differences can be resolved 
chiles said the talks between the two chambers would begin next 
week and he hoped go quickly 
but sen pete v domenici of new mexico the senior republican 
on the budget committee said it is a more formidable challenge 
than i thought it would be in the wake of the deficit agreement 
the budget is a congressional resolution which does not require 
the presidents signature but it guides lawmakers as they pass 
their annual fiscal legislation 
congress has a selfimposed deadline of april 15 for finishing 
the budget it has failed to meet the deadline again but things 
are closer to being resolved at this date than they have been in 
recent years 
