the government says birth control pill 
manufacturers have agreed to phase out highestrogen pills based on 
a finding that they are no more effective than lowerdose pills and 
could heighten the risk of blood clotting 
the food and drug administration said thursday the three 
manufacturers gd searle and co ortho pharmaceutical corp and 
syntex corp will phase out distribution of the pills over a 
sixmonth period to allow physicians time to switch their patients 
to lowerdose estrogen pills 
the action follows a recommendation by an fda advisory panel 
that the highdose pills those containing more than 50 micrograms 
of estrogen be withdrawn because of the heightened risk of blood 
clotting 
i applaud the responsible decision of these manufacturers 
fda commissioner frank e young said in a statement low dose 
contraceptives are quite safe and for healthy young women are 
considered to be the most effective reversible means of preventing 
pregnancy 
the most commonly prescribed birth control pills contain 30 
micrograms to 35 micrograms of estrogen and are not affected by the 
phaseout the ones being withdrawn contain from 75 micrograms to 
100 micrograms of estrogen 
