<TEXT>
mail is a little musical out of place on a 
big broadway stage 
the show which opened thursday at the music box theater 
examines the anxieties of a sensitive 29yearold wouldbe 
novelist named alex who is having a midlife crisis 10 years too 
soon 
not exactly a novel idea for a musical but for much of the 
time the evening is fun in an obvious goodnatured sort of way 
seekers of sondheim significance and solemnity should look 
elsewhere 
the problem with mail is that the production relies on a 
gimmick to keep the story going and that gimmick falters during 
the second act no matter how busy director andrew cardiff keeps 
his actors and set designers 
the hook created by author jerry colker is simple an 
angstridden alex michael rupert disappears for four months and 
when he returns to his dingy new york apartment there is a pile of 
mail to open when he does the letters leap to life 
so does the complicated set designed by gerry hariton and vicki 
baral alexs letter writers jump out from behind doors walls and 
windows and pop out of the desk and bathtub one even makes an 
entrance through the refrigerator 
theres his bewildered girlfriend dana dumped just when she and 
alex were going to get married and franklin alexs best friend 
an idealist turned entrepreneur 
other correspondents include alexs gruff obnoxious father who 
wants his son to come back to the carburetor business in mineola 
long island and the writers vixenish literary agent who wants to 
get her client into bed before she gets him on the bestseller list 
their increasingly frantic missives are interrupted by overdue 
bills junk mail high school reunion letters and even sweepstakes 
announcements that sing and dance these interludes are among the 
best in the show its hard not to laugh when a contingent of con 
edison workers dressed in hard hats tshirts and short pants 
bully alex in time to a disco ditty called were gonna turn off 
your juice 
colker also wrote the lyrics for mail and rupert supplied 
the music with this large score nearly 30 numbers in all the 
duo makes good on the promise they demonstrated in 3 guys naked 
from the waist down an offbeat contemporary musical about the 
world of standup comics 
ruperts music for mail is eclectic ranging from pop to 
soul to ragtime to countrywestern the songs have a brash broadway 
sound the result of michael gibsons firstrate orchestrations at 
least one number a lament by the rejected girlfriend entitled 
its getting harder to love you would seem to have potential 
for a life outside of the show 
colkers amusing lyrics are more enticing than his slender 
story the tale starts to evaporate at the beginning of act 2 when 
alex has a momentous revelation he decides to see others as they 
see him that decision forces the letter writers to recapitulate 
their feelings about our hero its only a matter of time before 
alex neatly resolves his problems with each of them and with 
himself 
fortunately the show has been blessed with a fine cast rupert 
is a consumate hardworking musical comedy performer and he makes 
alex an ingratiating character we can care about 
mara getz as the lovesick dana possesses the shows best voice 
while brian mitchell the opportunistic best friend struts and 
swings with style only robert mandan as the insensitive father 
with problems of his own seems uncomfortable in the musical 
the show always seems to be in motion even when the story 
isnt most of the recent broadway musicals move but they dont 
dance grover dale has come up with some snappy if abbreviated 
dance routines recalling a style of musical comedy choreography 
that has gone out of fashion 
mail makes for a reasonably diverting entertainment 
especially if you dont think too hard about the wellworn message 
it delivers 
in other reviews 
howard kissel of the daily news writes this is a revue sketch 
idea that might have been amusing for 12 minutes the music is 
as facile and vapid as the characters who sing it 
but maybe someone should point out to young american writers 
that the world has many more appealing subjects than their not very 
interesting lives 
in the new york times frank rich asks is it possible that 
mail is a surreptitious advertisement for federal express 
</TEXT>
