<TEXT>
secretary of state george p shultz and three 
other grimfaced diplomats who signed the afghan accords studiously 
avoided the word peace to describe what they had achieved 
the tragic reality behind what shultz called a historic 
agreement is that the killing will go on in afghanistan as it did 
in vietnam for two years after henry kissinger put his signature on 
a similar accord in 1973 
yes the soviets pledged to remove their 115000 troops from 
afghanistan by feb 15 1989 
yes shultz left geneva and the signing ceremony in the united 
nations palace of justice talking about worldwide efforts to help 
afghan refugees return to villages no longer threatened by soviet 
napalm and helicopter gunships 
yes the agreement signed thursday by the foreign ministers of 
the government in kabul pakistan the united states and the soviet 
union opens the way for what shultz called afghan control over 
afghanistan 
although the soviets have not stated their intentions publicly 
the sad expectation is that that the soviets will continue to arm 
the afghan government they have backed for a decade and the afghan 
mujahadeen supported by the united states will continue receiving 
weapons from a cia pipeline 
today however a high administration official speaking on 
condition he not be identified said the united states still hopes 
that the soviets may elect to end shipments to afghanistan and let 
that long war wind down 
the united states tried to get the soviets to agree to a mutual 
cutoff of weaponry but that effort failed so it is likely the 
afghan rivals will continue receiving the means to kill each 
others adherents 
the accords signed in geneva do not end the war they merely 
begin the end to soviet troop participation in it shultz 
acknowledged the agreement was not perfect but he and 
officials who traveled with him to geneva were clearly satisfied 
with what had been accomplished 
the united states its allies the islamic world and most of the 
rest of the world have been railing against the soviets for more 
than eight years for sending troops to afghanistan to bring that 
withdrawal about after the loss of an estimated million afghan 
lives was a major victory shultz said prompting him to proclaim 
history has been made today 
the agreement also will permit the united states to step back a 
bit from deep involvement in afghanistan affairs the officials 
said 
after all before the soviets turned afghanistan into a 
superpower sore point the united states had little interest in the 
incessant warfare within afghans tribal society 
the soviet decision to withdraw could lead to the restoration of 
afghanistan to that shelf of countries the united states need not 
worry about and the officials seemed pleased at that prospect 
there was a touch of irony to the signing ceremony in that it 
took place in the same chamber where the superpowers blessed a 1955 
indochina accord that eventually failed 
the parallels between afghanistan in the 1980s and vietnam 
particularly in the 1970s are inescapable 
a superpower bogged down in an unpopular war at home and abroad 
realizing its superior firepower cannot defeat a tenacious 
guerrilla force armed by another superpower signs an agreement 
permitting disengagement with honor 
in 1973 secretary of state kissinger set the stage in the paris 
accords for us troop withdrawal turning the struggle over to the 
wellstocked south vietnamese by april 1975 the north vietnamese 
had won 
on thursday soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze who 
signed the troop withdrawal pledge said supplies to the 
legitimate government of afghan leader najib would continue 
shevardnadze sounding vaguely like the american officials of 
the 1970s tried to put the best face on what had happened 
how will soviet generals swallow their defeat he was asked at a 
news conference soviet generals dont think they lost the war 
he replied 
he feigned ignorance of a wellpublicized soviet academicians 
assertion that moscows initial decision in 1979 to send in the 
troops was a mistake 
the soviet union went into afghanistan to help a besieged 
legitimate government he said 
behind the gloss us officials said was a clear soviet 
determination to end its involvement a determination unthreatened 
by lastminute finagling over the continuation of superpower 
assistance 
asked if shevardnadzes condemnation of us assistance for the 
rebels could unravel the agreement one official laughed and 
declared they arent looking for a pretext to stay 
the accepted wisdom at the pentagon and the state department has 
the najib government collapsing eventually because it has little 
support among afghans 
yet there is no consensus in washington on how soon that could 
happen 
the most graceful transition to peace could come about through a 
further mediation effort by diego cordovez the united nations 
official who led the negotiations that resulted in thursdays 
accord 
cordovez has agreed to begin talks with the factions on creating 
an interim government to supplant the marxist najib regime 
in the meantime najib and his enemies the mujahadeen vow to 
continue the struggle and the killing will continue 
