the tragedies of multiple suicides by young 
people can provide lessons for other communities to follow in the 
future according to a new report by the national centers for 
disease control 
on march 11 1987 in bergenfield nj two young men 18 and 
19 and two young women 16 and 17 committed suicide by locking 
themselves in a garage and sitting inside a car with the motor 
running 
within days school officials identified other students they 
felt might be at risk counseling was provided to young people and 
a local suicide hotline and a walkin counseling center were 
started 
the cdc report as is the agencys custom did not name the new 
jersey town where the four young people died on that date but 
bergenfield has been identified in numerous news reports about the 
deaths 
after an investigation the cdc noted in its weekly report 
thursday that when a suicide cluster does occur an extraordinary 
amount of community effort and resources is temporarily devoted to 
suicide prevention 
such a response is appropriate the atlantabased health 
agency said it is prudent for a community faced with a suicide 
cluster to make every effort to anticipate and prevent additional 
suicides among susceptible individuals 
the cdc said communities should consider contingency plans for 
suicide clusters and may want to consider implementing a suicide 
response plan before a cluster has begun many suicide clusters 
the agency said have followed one or more deaths due to injuries 
among young people 
planning ahead can keep communities from reinventing the 
wheel during their own tragedies said dr patrick ocarroll of 
the cdc 
theres no reason for every single community that runs into 
this to try to start from scratch theres experience they can try 
to take advantage of ocarroll said 
bergenfield a suburban community six miles west of new york 
had an annual suicide rate of seven per 100000 during 198084 
significantly lower than the national rate of 12 per 100000 cdc 
researchers found 
