deeply distressed over a resolution approved by the danish 
parliament which closes a loophole in a government ban on ships 
carrying nuclear weapons into danish ports 
the resolution approved thursday by a 7558 vote requires the 
government to inform visiting naval vessels of denmarks 
antinuclear policy denmark has a nuclear ban policy but has not 
been asking such vessels if they are carrying nuclear weapons 
state department spokesman charles redman said implementation of 
the danish resolution in a way which is inconsistent with the us 
policy of not discussing which ships carry nuclear weapons would 
undercut nato security the united states has a longstanding 
policy of neither confirming nor denying the presence of nuclear 
weapons aboard its ships 
this policy is central to the us ability to fulfill its nato 
commitments redman said we are not going to change it 
it would have extremely serious consequences for usdanish 
defense cooperation he said adding that the impact of this 
issue extends beyond bilateral relations 
it goes to the very heart of the meaning and interlocking 
nature of our mutual commitments within the nato alliance he 
said 
redman said the policy of withholding information about the 
presence of nuclear weapons is aimed at keeping terrorists and 
saboteurs in the dark and makes effective attacks on us forces 
more difficult 
