<TEXT>
the third fullscale test firing of 
the redesigned space shuttle booster rocket will be conducted 
wednesday morton thiokol inc announced 
morton thiokol spokesman rocky raab said the 1 pm horizontal 
firing of the 126footlong rocket will last two minutes the 
booster 12 feet in diameter contains 11 million pounds of 
propellant 
during the second fullscale firing on dec 23 the rockets 
nasadesigned nozzle boot ring broke apart the boot ring about 
two inches thick protects a flexible bearing that allows the 
nozzle to swivel and steer the rocket 
company officials said the test will incorporate the nozzle boot 
ring designed by morton thiokol which performed successfully during 
the first fullscale test last august 
wednesdays firing although the third of its kind at the 
wasatch operations test site is the first of three required to 
qualify the new booster for flight subsequent tests are scheduled 
june 3 and july 6 
the august and december tests evaluated primary and alternate 
elements of solid rocket motor design raab said 
he said the center field joint on the motor to be tested next 
week has been assembled with an intentional manufacturingtype 
flaw in the bonded insulations jseal 
this defect may allow hot gases to penetrate the bonded 
insulation and reach an oring barrier but raab added that 
shortduration test firings with similar defects have shown that 
such defects tend to seal under motor pressure preventing the 
release of gases 
the escape of such superhot gases from a morton thiokol booster 
was blamed for the jan 28 1986 explosion of the shuttle 
challenger and deaths of its seven crew members 
the resumption of shuttle missions is tentatively scheduled for 
aug 4 although nasa officials have said technical problems could 
further delay the launch 
</TEXT>
