<TEXT>
contra rebel leaders returning to 
managua on friday some after years in exile can expect to find 
considerably more misery but not many tangible changes in their 
capital 
the trip by the directorate of the miamibased nicaraguan 
resistance was to further work started last month to reach a 
lasting ceasefire and end more than six years of civil war 
just a few months back such a visit seemed impossible 
but haggling and compromise on both sides coupled with a need 
to end the grueling war made the trip a necessity 
the contras 45member delegation will find that the leftist 
sandinistas still maintain a firm control on the daytoday 
workings of the government although their popularity has slipped 
the capital still is dusty and hot this time of year though 
increased poverty and population are evident 
vast open lots left barren since the 1972 earthquake have not 
been filled the walls of homes and buildings bear prosandinista 
and marxist grafitti a steep hillside bears the initials of the 
sandinista party 
a large black iron statue in a downtown plaza shows a fighter 
with one fist in the air the other arm raised and holding a 
sovietdesigned ak47 rifle redandblack sandinista flags fly 
everywhere 
thousands of people most from the rural north flooded into the 
capital and its environs to escape the ravages of war managua is 
home to about a third of the nations population of 3 million 
wooden shacks sit in dusty lots 
water has been rationed for the past few years some 
neighborhoods do without for as little as two days a week while 
others receive water only a few hours per week 
there are shortages of everything from spare parts for cars to 
the basics of rice and beans 
discontent was on the rise earlier this year because of the 
economic conditions the scarcities and the mandatory draft but 
attitudes changed last month when the ceasefire talks made it seem 
that peace could be a reality 
the mood in the capital has been one of guarded hope with most 
residents acknowledging there never has been a point so close to 
ending the war 
the contra delegation was headed by the resistances board made 
up of adolfo calero aristides sanchez alfredo cesar pedro 
joaquin chamorro and maria azucena ferrey 
