the capital spending survey also eases fears running in the 
other direction that dampened consumer demand would lead to a 
recession this year 
economists are looking to manufacturing for export and capital 
spending to keep the economy growing the cheaper dollar is 
creating more demand overseas for usmanufactured goods and 
capital spending is increasing so factories can meet that demand 
in 1986 investment spending fell by 26 percent as american 
companies battled stiff foreign competition 
for 1988 manufacturing firms expected to boost spending by 89 
percent after a 11 percent increase last year 
