<TEXT>
a federal advisory panel issued updated 
guidelines on treating high blood pressure friday citing the 
potential value of new classes of drugs but emphasizing the need to 
prescribe the lowest effective dose of any medication 
intended primarily for physicians the recommendations were 
described by the chairman of the national institutes of health 
panel as a sort of bible or gospel of treatment 
abram v chobanian incoming dean of the boston university 
school of medicine added that the suggestions were based on an 
eightmonth review of latest research to update the guidelines last 
issued four years ago 
he noted that two new classes of drugs socalled calcium 
antagonists and enzyme inhibitors have been approved for treating 
high blood pressure since the last report 
for many patients they may cause fewer symptomatic and 
biochemical side effects than diuretics and beta blockers he 
said referring to the only high blood pressure drugs on the market 
in 1984 
but chobanian emphasized that the updated guidelines call for 
lower initial doses for most drugs than we did in 1984 
the point here is that smaller doses mean fewer side 
effects he said at a news conference this a critical 
advantage because the side effects of traditional antihypertensive 
drugs have been a major stumbling block to keeping patients on 
their treatment 
among other things the widely used diuretics can cause 
impotence and excessive loss of potassium in some patients 
we recommend that some patients especially those with mild 
hypertension start with nondrug treatments said chobanian by 
that i mean reducing weight limiting sodium and alcohol stopping 
smoking exercising and perhaps using biofeedback and relaxation 
techniques 
the report urges physicians to carefully monitor those patients 
who do need drug treatment with an eye to reducing the dosage or 
perhaps eliminating such medication 
the updated guidelines also say people with high blood pressure 
should drink no more than the equivalent of two beers a day down 
from three in the 1984 report and emphasizes that lowering blood 
pressure alone is not a major reducer of heart attacks if the 
patient does not also control other risk factors especially 
smoking and high blood cholesterol levels 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

