<TEXT>
the judge in the irancontra trial warned 
friday against the unauthorized disclosure of some 300000 
classified documents expected to be turned over to the defense by 
prosecutor lawrence e walsh 
in an order detailing procedures for handling the documents by 
the defense us district judge gerhard a gesell warned that 
unauthorized disclosure of classified information may constitute 
violations of united states criminal laws 
persons subject to this order are advised that direct or 
indirect unauthorized disclosure retention or negligent handling 
of classified documents or information could cause serious damage 
and in some cases exceptionally grave damage to the national 
security of the united states or may be used to the advantage of a 
foreign nation against the interests of the united states the 
judge said 
the ninepage order requires that the defendants their lawyers 
and any witnesses must obtain approval of the courtdesignated 
security officer before gaining access to classified documents 
access will be granted on a needtoknow basis and the 
defendants their lawyers and witnesses must sign an agreement not 
to make unauthorized disclosures of the information contained in 
the documents gesell said 
any violation of the terms of this order shall be immediately 
brought to the attention of the court and may result in a charge of 
contempt of court and possible reference for criminal 
prosecution gesell said 
marine lt col oliver l north and former national security 
adviser john m poindexter are accused of conspiring with arms 
dealers albert hakim and retired air force maj gen richard v 
secord to divert profits illegally from the usiran arms sales to 
the nicaraguan contra rebels 
at a hearing tuesday independent counsel walsh said that as 
many as 300000 classified documents are being reviewed by an 
interagency government task force walsh said he expected that 
50000 documents relevant to the case will be ready for defense 
review by months end 
gesell ordered that the defense is entitled to review the rest 
of the material to determine if it is relevant to their case when 
the matter goes to trial 
the order requires that lawyers can only work with the documents 
or discuss them with each other or witnesses in the special 
security facility that is being constructed by the court security 
officer 
gesell prescribed a type of word processing equipment which is 
apparently resistant to electronic eavesdropping to be used by the 
defense for preparing court pleadings based on the materials 
all pleadings dealing with classified information must be 
prepared in the facility and filed under seal with the court 
security officer who will delete classified references before the 
briefs are placed in the public file gesell ordered 
before any classified document is introduced into evidence at 
the trial it must be declassified by the government agencies that 
produced it 
if the government refuses to declassify a document the 
classified information procedures act empowers the court to 
substitute a statement of facts that the material would prove 
the court could also agreed to delete certain classified 
markings that reveal intelligence methods but were not pertinent to 
the case 
gesell gave the defense until april 29 to file a challenge to 
the application fo the classified information statute to the case 
the defense complained that the law requires procedures that 
inhibit their ability to prepare their case 
