navy heart surgeon donal m billig was 
freed friday from fort leavenworth where he had been held for two 
years after his conviction in the deaths of three patients was 
overturned on appeal 
the us navymarine court of military review ruled thursday 
that the evidence was simply not sufficient 
billig 57 was released about 11 am according lt col john 
gerlinger who said no other information about billigs plans would 
be released at his request billig told military authorities that 
he would not meet with reporters 
the navy has 20 days to ask the appeals court to reconsider 
billig who automatically returns to active duty with his 
previous rank of commander probably will be assigned to a reserve 
center in kansas city while the navy decides to appeal said navy 
spokeswoman lt janet mescus 
billig is also eligible for 120000 in back pay 
billig was chief heart surgeon at the navys bethesda naval 
hospital in maryland he was convicted in 1986 of two counts of 
involuntary manslaughter and one count of negligent homicide in the 
deaths of three patients 
he also was convicted on 18 of 24 counts of dereliction of duty 
in other operations and was sentenced to four years in prison 
the appeals court said prosecutors lost sight of the fact that 
coronary artery bypass surgery is an inherently risky business 
prosecutors had argued that billig used questionable surgical 
techniques but they never produced evidence or testimony to 
demonstrate his work constituted criminal conduct the appeals 
court said 
we shall set aside all findings of guilty based on this 
factual insufficiency of the evidence the court said 
prosecutors described billig as an egocentric man who hid the 
fact that he was nearly blind in one eye and continued performing 
complex operations despite warnings that he was killing patients 
the appeals court said it was troubled by billigs conviction 
because his courtmartial involved criminal charges as opposed to 
civil claims for damages based on negligence 
we are not convinced beyond a reasonable doubt that the deaths 
that formed the basis of the appellants conviction were due to any 
negligence simple or otherwise on his part the appeals court 
said 
