a psychologist was indicted friday on charges 
of submitting false data to win a 200000 federal research grant 
a federal prosecutor said the charges were the first of their kind 
in the nation 
stephen e breuning 35 was charged in connection with a grant 
received in 1982 from the national institute of mental health in 
bethesda while he was a faculty member at the university of 
pittsburgh medical school 
the money already has been repaid by the university us 
attorney breckinridge willcox said in a statement 
breuning now director of psychological services and behavorial 
treatment at the polk center in polk pa submitted a 1981 grant 
request for a study titled stimulant drug use with mentally 
retarded children while at the university from 1982 to 1984 the 
statement said 
the indictment said breunings applications cited the results of 
seven studies of hyperactive mentally retarded children 
breuning knew the studies had not been completed at the 
university of pittsburgh as described and that the studies 
that were ongoing were not obtaining the results as described 
the indictment said 
willcox said that the indictment is believed to be first time 
criminal charges have been brought against an individual in 
connection with falsified research 
we have addressed a problem that i suspect is more 
widespread than we think fraudulent research data in the medical 
field willcox said let this investigation send a clear 
message to doctors and researchers who play fast and loose with 
their research that they will have to deal with the criminal 
justice system in addition to their peer review panels 
