<TEXT>
many analysts who are still skittish about the 
investment outlook these days point to the uninspired behavior 
lately of utility stocks 
last week while the dow jones average of 30 industrials briefly 
touched a new high since the october crash dow joness average of 
15 utilities lagged behind 
when it dipped below 170 late last week the utility average 
stood more than 10 percent below where it was on jan 29 
the performance of utility stocks as a group is a good gauge 
of the interestrate environment said anthony sorrentino an 
analyst at standard amp poors corp in the firms weekly advisory 
publication the outlook 
it is also he added often a leading indicator of stock 
prices in general 
utility stocks tend to respond quickly to changing expectations 
about the interestrate outlook for a couple of wellknown reasons 
for one thing since utilities are heavy borrowers to finance 
their capital needs interest rates are an important element of 
their costs of doing business 
besides that most investors in utility stocks are very 
yieldconscious and thus tend to push the stocks prices up and 
down in close alignment with fluctuations in the bond market 
in the great bull market the dow jones utility average was the 
first of the widely recognized indicators to peak out at 22783 on 
jan 22 1987 
any investors who used that as a sell signal missed out on 
the dramatic gains in industrial stock prices that continued 
through august of last year 
but they also would have been safely out of the way when 
interest rates surged upward last spring and when stock prices 
crashed in the fall 
the recent weakness in utilities sorrentino says is reason 
for concern as it suggests that investors believe interest rates 
are headed higher 
of course interestrate expectations can change sometimes very 
quickly the merrill lynch market letter maintains that utility 
stocks generally appear to be oversold we think they could do 
better in the months ahead 
even if utilities do not come on strong argues greg smith an 
analyst at prudentialbache securities they are not an infallible 
guide to what the rest of the market might do 
utilities fell in 1977 he points out and then industrial 
stocks rose for the next three years 
the poor performance of the utility averages signals bad 
problems for the overall stock market to many investors especially 
since the divergence developed prior to the crash of last year 
he said 
theyre waiting for another shoe to fall i think its a 
mistake to look for a matching shoe 
to mix metaphors a little i would point out that the same 
lightning rarely strikes the stock market twice in a row 
in smiths view the markets early1988 rally drew its force 
not from value considerations based on such things as interest 
rates but rather from strong corporate earnings 
utilities wont work but not because another crisis is in the 
making he said they wont work because this isnt a 
valuationdriven market anymore 
the bottom in interest rates is very well established now as 
a result the industrial averages the utility averages and 
interest rates are no longer going to move together 
this is a more advanced stage of the stock market cycle and i 
dont know of any reliable tool to predict its duration 
</TEXT>
