<DOCNO> AP880415-0266 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chairmen of the new york stock exchange 
and the chicago mercantile exchange say they expect agreement soon 
on a plan to halt trading in stocks and stockindex futures when 
the markets rise or fall 200 to 300 points in one day 
the heads of the two fiercely competitive exchanges new york 
for stocks and chicago for futures on thursday told a house panel 
examining the october stock market collapse that they hoped to 
agree on the plan within the next month 
however leo melamed chairman of the chicago exchanges 
executive committee and john j phelan chairman and chief 
executive officer of the new york stock exchange differed on just 
how far the markets should move before trading is interrupted 
phelan said the trading should not be halted until the dow jones 
industrial average moves 250 to 300 points while melamed said the 
limits should be in the range of 200 to 250 points 
melamed and phelan said since october they have met several 
times in an effort to achieve greater coordination congressional 
leaders particularly senate banking committee chairman william 
proxmire dwis and house finance subcommittee chairman edward j 
markey dmass had been complaining about the lack of progress 
in talks among the exchanges and among federal regulatory agencies 
youve got to let the market seek its own level but there 
comes a time when a systematic halt a safety net that is known 
in advance is helpful phelan said 
in the futures market we are not uncomfortable with price 
limits we already have them melamed said it just depends on 
where you draw the line he said short halts in trading are a 
necessary evil perhaps but something we could live with 
phelan said the purpose of the halts would be to allow the 
market to stop and take a look at itself he said they should 
be more than 30 minutes but should not last all day 
both chairmen told the house finance subcommittee that president 
reagans new working group on the markets has indicated a 
circuitbreaker plan is a high priority 
currently the big board limits a form of computerized trading 
known as index arbitrage which links the new york stock markets 
with the chicago futures markets once the dow moves 50 points 
either up or down 
the chicago exchange has set daily price limits on its standard 
amp poors 500 stock index future which is based on stocks traded on 
the big board there is an opening price limit that restricts any 
move during the first l0 minutes of trading to the equivalent of 
roughly 40 points on the dow and a daily price limit equivalent to 
between 120 and 150 dow points 
but such circuit breakers are not coordinated between new york 
and chicago 
melamed also said regulation of the nations financial markets 
by a single federal agency would do a great disservice to the 
marketplace and that it is neither warranted nor wise 
currently the commodities futures trading commission oversees 
the nations futures markets and the securities and exchange 
commission regulates securities trading 
phelan said he believes one regulator should eventually be in 
charge of all the markets 
we believe that ultimately there should be a unified 
regulator for all equityrelated products phelan testified 
but more immediately it is much more important that we 
strengthen the clearing and settlement process as well as put in 
place an allmarket circuit breaker in the event of a major market 
decline 
melamed said the roles of the cftc and the sec are so different 
that they should not be combined 
the number of true intermarket issues are few and limited in 
scope melamed told the panel moreover they must be resolved 
now not when the next crisis occurs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

