<TEXT>
eastman kodak co has given its workforce 
in panama a 15day paid furlough because of the extreme difficulty 
in doing business there a company spokesman said today 
the catalyst for the shutdown of kodaks marketing facility 
retail film and camera shops and minilab processing centers was 
last fridays economic sanctions imposed by president reagan said 
kodak spokesman henry kaska 
we werent ordered to close but it just doesnt make sense to 
stay open kaska said we are not permitted to pay our utility 
bill we cant pay the phone bill we were also concerned about the 
security of our people traveling in that country 
the sanctions were ordered april 8 by reagan in an effort to 
force military leader manuel antonio noriega to surrender his hold 
on the central american country 
they include prohibiting payments to the noriega regime by all 
us citizens and organizations in panama freezing the us assets 
of the panamanian government and prohibiting any person or company 
in the united states from making any payments to the regime 
kaska said he didnt have an exact figure on the number of kodak 
employees but estimated it was less than 1000 he said the 
furlough went into effect tuesday 
after the 15 days well reevaluate and reassess and determine 
whether there should be another furlough kaska said we hope 
the situation will stabilize within a month 
