texaco inc announced friday it will resume 
paying a quarterly dividend and will sell off an additional 2 
billion in assets as part of its restructuring 
at its first meeting since texaco emerged from chapter 11 
federal bankruptcy court reorganization on april 7 the oil giants 
board of directors authorized a 75cent quarterly dividend a move 
analysts said is intended to bolster shareholder support for the 
current management team 
in closing trading on the new york stock exchange texaco jumped 
162 to 4875 
texaco had been barred from paying dividends after it filed for 
bankruptcy protection on april 12 1987 in the wake of its epic 
legal battle with pennzoil co the dividend will be paid june 10 to 
shareholders of record may 3 
in addition to authorizing the dividend directors said they 
planned to sell off 5 billion in assets to help reduce the 
companys debt load 
texaco said in its 1987 annual report that it hoped to raise at 
least 3 billion through the sale of assets but fridays action 
increased that amount by 2 billion 
james w kinnear texacos president and chief executive 
officer said in a statement that the resumption of dividends at 
a substantial rate demonstrates texacos confidence that this 
expanded restructuring will enable us to build a more profitable 
company on a solid core of our most productive assets 
while texaco can afford the roughly 726 million a year in 
dividend payments experts noted that the extra expense will eat up 
nearly 100 percent of the companys projected earnings for the year 
the 3ashare annual dividend is not justified by texacos 
current earnings prospects said bruce lazier vice president for 
energy investments at prescott ball amp turben inc they probably 
will not earn much more than the 3 a share rate 
