<TEXT>
lawyers for some 1300 former xerox corp 
employees claiming they lost their jobs because of age 
discrimination asked a federal appeals court friday to allow them 
to sue for damages in a class action 
the case has bounced around the federal court system for five 
years and now it has bounced back to the third us circuit court 
of appeals where two judges said they were troubled that a lower 
court without considering statistical evidence had decertified a 
class of victims of an alleged pattern or practice of age 
discrimination 
according to briefs filed in the case xerox terminated forced 
to retire or denied promotion to at least 1300 people between may 
1980 and april 1983 in order to reduce its work force the lower 
court held they were not part of a class action because they had 
different jobs and different risks 
that is error said attorney robert dietz representing 13 
former salesmen of xerox facsimile devices who brought the appeal 
seeking to reinstate a 1984 order by the us district court in new 
jersey that had created a conditional class 
after nearly an hour of oral argument judges william 
hutchinson max rosenn and anthony scirica took the case under 
advisement 
a decision is not expected until sometime this summer 
robert jaffe another lawyer representing the employees said 
we are fighting the procedural barriers erected by a 
wellfinanced firm who have consistently denied that the reduction 
in force imposed by xerox targeted older workers even though the 
evidence we provided conclusively supports it 
you say the lower court failed to consider the statistical 
evidence or even company documents that supported it when it 
denied a class action designation asked rosenn 
right responded jaffe we ask you to instruct the trial 
court to consider that we say xerox conducted fraud on its older 
workers the undisputed facts of discrimination come from the 
companys own records what the lower court did was a clear error 
of law 
attorney robert del tufo representing xerox disagreed and 
contended that charges of discrimination must be proved 
separately by each claimant 
rosenn interjected that what troubles me is that in the 
district court opinion there is no discussion of the evidence 
hutchinson said he too was troubled because the judge 
didnt say what he found and that appears to be clear error 
rosenn added he ignored the statistical evidence and said it 
wasnt relevant should he have disregarded it thats what we have 
to decide 
del tufo argued that the statistical evidence is wrong and is 
irrelevant 
the federal equal employment opportunity commission in a friend 
of the court brief noted it is difficult to prove specific acts 
of discrimination and that statistics may often be the only 
available evidence of clandestine and covert discrimination 
it joined the plaintiffs in asking that the class be certified 
contending that the lower court committed legal error 
